language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 1: Set of Partitions
$
$ Domain:  set (size w) of partition (regular, numParts g, partSize s) from Golfers
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - There are exactly w weeks (set size w)
$   - Each week is a partition of all golfers into groups
$   - Each partition has exactly g groups (numParts g)
$   - Each group has exactly s golfers (partSize s, regular)
$   - Disjointness: no golfer appears in two groups within a week (partition semantics)
$   - Full coverage: every golfer plays every week (partition semantics)
$   - Weeks are unordered (set semantics eliminates week-ordering symmetry)
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   - Only the pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
$
$ This is the most information-rich formulation. The partition domain encodes
$ group structure, sizes, disjointness, and coverage. The set-of eliminates
$ week ordering. Only the inter-week pairing constraint remains.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s
letting Golfers be new type of size nGolfers

find sched : set (size w) of partition (regular, numParts g, partSize s) from Golfers

$ Pairing constraint: no two golfers play in the same group more than once
such that
    forAll p1 : Golfers .
        forAll p2 : Golfers .
            p1 != p2 ->
            (sum week in sched .
                sum part in parts(week) .
                    toInt(p1 in part /\ p2 in part)
            ) <= 1
